<font color="#FF0000">MY BROTHERS KEEPER</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 18  8:38:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art and All,<br>
Especially Gary, <br><br>
That picture Art described of the men in the business suit, gray beard, leaning his head toward his comrades reflective images on the wall, I could have swore that picture was me, when I first saw it. <br><br>
A reflection of what I looked like when I first visited the wall. Middle age- suit/tie, shirtsleeves coped up; boy do I remember that day. How many of us does that picture reflect? In our hearts, all of us.<br><br>
I knew that when I started this thread it was going to strike us hard. The bravery, trust, honor, respect we had for each other has already emerged from prior threads, but there are others silent shadows that dwell in our pass that sometimes we wonder about but never share. We don't share them with our loved ones, or even visit them in our memories. They are there honored in the deep crevices of our inner heart. There are some Marines I shared many fund memories with that I wish I could locate and share some more. There are others that have gone on before me and I will only meet them on the other side of life. I miss them, trusted them with my life and they trusted me with theirs. Those I can only visit in my heart and honor them at the wall.  <br><br>
If anyone of you ever wants to visit the wall and never has, I would be honored to go with you. <br>
You all have been a great encouragement to me to keep writing my book, as Ed once warned me, it has been painful at times, but sharing some of those incidents here with you all has helped me a lot, more then anyone of you will ever realize.<br><br>
Here, I have laughed with you, cried with you and even became angry at times, angry not at any one of you but at the injustice, the shame we have had to endure. I would have been honored to have anyone of you at my side in Nam, and I would have done all that I could to assure your return home. <br><br>
But I wasn't there with you. Those men in your memories and hearts were. The ones that come to mind, yesterday, today and tomorrow. I wish they were here today, every one of them. But some paid the ultimate price for what they believed in; and today we live also for them. Others came home and disappeared into a shadow world of pain and suffering where we may never find them. But their spirit and the honor they shared with us is still alive in our hearts and that is why, we're here. Honoring them with our memories and respect.<br>
In Peace and War they are our Brothers<br><br>
Cook<br><br>

